data.content:
**Yes, C# fully supports `stackalloc`'d `Span<nint>` and `Span<nuint>`.** The test confirms both work without issues:

```csharp
Span<nint>  signedSpan   = stackalloc nint[4];
Span<nuint> unsignedSpan = stackalloc nuint[4];
```

On this 64-bit system each element is 8 bytes. This has been supported since C# 9 / .NET 5 when `nint`/`nuint` were introduced as first-class types — they're valid in any context where other unmanaged value types (like `int`, `long`) are allowed, including `stackalloc`.
